Communicated by:
ProMED

[Peruvian authorities recently confirmed that the virus involved in the pelican outbreak was the Eurasian H5N1 first detected in January 2022 in the Atlantic coast of North America. Information about the typification of the Peruvian isolates is requested. In the Americas, many Anseriformes and Charadriformes migrate latitudinally in the Americas, some connecting North and South America through the Pacific, Mississippi and Atlantic flyways. The long distance spread of HPAI H5N1 is believed to be carried out by some migrant Anseriformes. A species of interest because it links North and South America through migration is the blue-winged teal (_Anas discors_). Many blue-winged teal that breed in North America winter in northern South America, including Peru. A recent study (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/tbed.12244) found no evidence of South American lineage genes detected in influenza A viruses (IAVs) isolated from blue-winged teal sampled in the United States, supporting restricted viral gene flow between the United States and southern South America. However, it is plausible that blue-winged teal redistribute IAVs between North American breeding grounds and wintering areas throughout the Neotropics, including northern South America. - Mod.PMB

